2) Quick start

- Requires SWI-Prolog 8.*.* or higher
- See the O-ETB User Manual for details concerning prerequisites, installation and use.

In the O-ETB/src directory, run make. This will create the 'etb' executable in BUILD.
It can then be executed as '../BUILD/etb'.
Alternatively etb can be compiled and run directly from within Prolog (start swipl from shell).
To do this and run a simple pattern instantiation and view the result:
   % swipl
     ... Prolog Banner ...
   ? [etb].
   ? etb.
   etb> instantiate_pattern('person', ['Marius', 'Programming'], 'ac1').
   etb> ac_export('ac1.txt', 'txt').
   etb> halt.
   %
This example can also be found as the predefined proc 'ex1' in procs_etb.pl.

Then, export the result of the previous instantiation to the CAP as HTML:
   % swipl
     ... Prolog Banner ...
   ? [etb].
   ? etb.
   etb> update_ongoing.
   etb> attach_assurance_repository('ac1').
   etb> ac_export('ac1-html', 'html').
   etb> halt.
   %
This example can be found as the predefined proc 'ex2' in procs_etb.pl.

To generate a small complete assurance case:
   % swipl
     ... Prolog Banner ...
   ? [etb].
   ? etb.
   etb> proc(ex3,verbose).
        ...
   etb> halt.
   % 
A web browser can them be used to view the assurance case by opening the .index file
in the created REPOSITORY/CASES/ac2 directory and navigating from there.
(This example runs the predefined proc 'ex3' in procs_etb.pl.

